Based on the N2 adsorption/desorption isotherms experiment, the BMO, CQDs/BIS and BMO/CQDs/BIS exhibited type Ⅳ isotherm and type H3 hysteresis loops (Fig. 3
                        a). All the above samples possessed a mesoporous structure. Furthermore, the pore size distribution diagram also proved that the synthesized composite material was mesoporous (Fig. 3b). In addition, the pore volume (0.1920 cm3/g), pore size (22.7 nm) and specific surface area (59.5 m2/g) of the composite BMO/CQDs/BIS were significantly higher than those of the monomer material BMO and CQDs/BIS (Table 1
                        ). More adsorption sites on composites could improve the efficiency of photocatalysis performance and shorten the distance of surface catalysis behavior.
